deum: cf. on superum, l. 4. regina deum: Juno, the wife of Jupiter. volvere: ‘to undergo,' suggesting the notiou either of rolling a burden along or of passing through a round of mishaps. Like adire, it depends on impulerit ; the infin. is used more freely in poetry than in prose, in which we should here have had ut and subj. (518. vi).

10. pietate: neither piety nor pity quite, but faithful observ- ance of duty whether to gods, parents, fellow-men, or country. Trans. ‘goodness.’ Aeneas is constantly called pins by Virgil, partly from his filial devotion to his father, partly from his dutiful obedience to the voice of the gods and to the leading of fate.
